Observation Details: **Very rare! Found yesterday midday on CBC by Roger Horn, and also observed and photographed at dusk yesterday by TBJ and me. Foraging and roving about the roadside hedge very energetically in the morning sun. Only prior December eBird records in the east north of Florida of any Warbling Vireo are singles from NS, OH, MD, NC, GA. Occurrence of “Western” in the east clouded in uncertainty due to difficulty of field ID, but certainly very rare. This individual had retained juvenile wing coverts and a strikingly small bill, the former trait apparently diagnostic for swainsoni at this date, and the latter strongly supportive, and at this extreme perhaps also diagnostic. [see “Voelker, G., and S. Rohwer (1998). Contrasts in scheduling of molt and migration in eastern and western Warbling Vireos. Auk 115 (1):142-155,” as well as “Pyle - Identification Guide to North American Birds. Part I,”] A targeted examination of specimens at the AMNH after this observation was also consistent with the above resources. Poop sample collected some time after this observation, and will potentially undergo DNA analysis at ANSP. Excellent close views this morning, and good photos (best by TBJ on different checklist) and video.

Observation Details: I was able to get excellent photos of this bird. They will be attached later. I viewed the vireo with my binoculars at a distance of 25 feet.  The sun was at my back.  I saw a bird with a vireo type (thicker than a warbler) bill, pale supercillium, gray head, dark eye, pale eyeline with white below, gray to olive gray back, dark gray wings, olive tail, pale yellow wash on sides/flanks, and white belly. The legs and feet were gray/blue. Similar species eliminated were the Philadelphia Vireo which has yellow breast, belly and vent not seen on this bird.

Observation Details: **very rare; continuing bird found yesterday by Roger Horn; very good views down low in clematis and other viney vegetation; perhaps a **Western Warbling Vireo**: small, mostly dark bill, pale bar at tips of greater coverts (retained juv feathers), dark crown, and pale underparts with a minor yellow-buff wash to flanks and breast; photos  *edit 6/26/2023 - changing to “Western” Warbling Vireo on the basis of mitochondrial DNA analysis by Dr. Jason Weckstein/ ANS in combination with plumage characteristics

Refound today by Bob Curry as it flitted about in shrubs and low tree branches, mostly at, slightly above or below eye level. It was very active catching prey (flying insect in one photo) on the southeast side, sheltered from the wind. Grey crown and nape, greenish-grey mantle and white below with pale yellow wash on flanks. White supercilium and lores. Pale bill with dark tip. Faint line behind eye. Seen first on 29 November by Julie Bowen, then Ana Santos, and reported on 1 December by Laura Murray. Great winter bird. Record late for the GTA - per Glenn Coady on Ontario Bird Alert Discord.

Drab gray color above, white below, slight yellow tint on flanks, thick white eyebrow with light gray eyeline. After researching differences between the PHVI and the WAVI I came across some ID contrasts between the two in the Crossley ID Guide for Eastern Birds (2011) which stated that the WAVI lacks contrast between the primary and greater coverts and it shows the yellow being brightest the breast sides as opposed to being brightest on the center of the breast on a PHVI.  These two ID marks seem to match the WAVI being seen here.  Seen in the gumbo limbo tree on south side of the  art institute building. The bird was seen early around 7:30am by Monica Higgins who mentioned it later flew off.  It showed up again at 9:20am and was spotted by Chad Cleland who got us on the bird. Greg Miller, Tiffany and Chad Cleland, and myself all had some nice views as the bird stuck around for about 5 minutes. While I was observing the bird It did not vocalize.

**Very rare! Found yesterday midday on CBC by Roger Horn, and also observed and photographed at dusk yesterday by TBJ and me. Foraging and roving about the roadside hedge very energetically in the morning sun. Only prior December eBird records in the east north of Florida of any Warbling Vireo are singles from NS, OH, MD, NC, GA. Occurrence of “Western” in the east clouded in uncertainty due to difficulty of field ID, but certainly very rare. This individual had retained juvenile wing coverts and a strikingly small bill, the former trait apparently diagnostic for swainsoni at this date, and the latter strongly supportive, and at this extreme perhaps also diagnostic. [see “Voelker, G., and S. Rohwer (1998). Contrasts in scheduling of molt and migration in eastern and western Warbling Vireos. Auk 115 (1):142-155,” as well as “Pyle - Identification Guide to North American Birds. Part I,”] A targeted examination of specimens at the AMNH after this observation was also consistent with the above resources. Poop sample collected some time after this observation, and will potentially undergo DNA analysis at ANSP. Excellent close views this morning, and good photos (best by TBJ on different checklist) and video.

Refound today by Bob Curry as it flitted about in shrubs and low tree branches, mostly at, slightly above or below eye level. It was very active catching prey (flying insect in one photo) on the southeast side, sheltered from the wind. Grey crown and nape, greenish-grey mantle and white below with pale yellow wash on flanks. White supercilium and lores. Pale bill with dark tip. Faint line behind eye. Seen first on 29 November by Julie Bowen, then Ana Santos, and reported on 1 December by Laura Murray. Great winter bird. Record late for the GTA - per Glenn Coady on Ontario Bird Alert Discord.

*Late; new eBird late date for Plymouth Co. by one day, although there are multiple November records in Massachusetts. Clearly two different birds, as they were found ~1.25 km away from each other, and the habitat is broken by large gaps. In addition, the first bird was left at 09:15, and the second bird was found at 09:55. Told from Philadelphia by the overall washed out facial pattern; i.e. the cap and lores were pale gray, not dark like in Philadelphia. Yellow was restricted to the flanks and undertail coverts. They are likely both HYs due to the outer rectrices coming to fine, tapered points, whereas adults should have more round-tipped outer rectrices. Observation Details: Added my first image of the bird on 15-Aug-2023, which gives, in my opinion, a better sense of the medium gray topsides and non-black crown. Original comments:  Adult WAVI, not sub-adult REVI. Photographed bird has: Very pale yellow flanks and undersides;  "plain-faced;" no wing bars.  Light grayish line through eye with practically white lores. rounded head; grayish topsides; dark eye; uniform, dark grayish crown; long tail and very light yellow vent. REVI should have: Some greenish/yellow topsides.  Black line through eye should be darker, especially in the lores. Crown should be dark grayish with distinctive black lining above the supercilium; facial disc should sharp light and dark areas, not the "soft" look of a WAVI facial disc; short tailed and yellow vent; larger bill; yellower in neck and face; PHVI: Smaller billed; smaller size than WAVI; darker and longer line through eye on PHVI; PHVI has central yellow wash in upper breast.. A first August record for Kerr Co.  Extremely few records this early In August in the surrounding counties. Bird made sweeps into the water feature, barely touching the water for a fraction of a second to get wet, then preened in Ash.

Drab gray color above, white below, slight yellow tint on flanks, thick white eyebrow with light gray eyeline. After researching differences between the PHVI and the WAVI I came across some ID contrasts between the two in the Crossley ID Guide for Eastern Birds (2011) which stated that the WAVI lacks contrast between the primary and greater coverts and it shows the yellow being brightest the breast sides as opposed to being brightest on the center of the breast on a PHVI.  These two ID marks seem to match the WAVI being seen here.  Seen in the gumbo limbo tree on south side of the  art institute building. The bird was seen early around 7:30am by Monica Higgins who mentioned it later flew off.  It showed up again at 9:20am and was spotted by Chad Cleland who got us on the bird. Greg Miller, Tiffany and Chad Cleland, and myself all had some nice views as the bird stuck around for about 5 minutes. While I was observing the bird It did not vocalize.

Observation Details: Continuing.  Photos. Scott Whittle was able to collect a poop specimen. 6/26/23 Update from Jason Weckstein DNA from feces sample resulted in this most likly being a Western Warbling Vireo

*Very rare after early Oct; found yesterday by Roger Horn. Retained juv wing coverts with buffy tips strongly suggestive of Western, which replaces coverts on wintering grounds (vs breeding grounds in Eastern); relatively small, dark bill and relatively darkish/saturated crown and back but duller/unsaturated underparts also suggestive of Western; photos  *June 2023 update: Changed to “Western” Warbling Vireo. Fecal sample collected from this bird was analyzed by Dr. Jason Weckstein and the DNA sequence data closely matched that of Western Warbling Vireo (and are quite divergent from Eastern Warbling Vireo).

*Late; new eBird late date for Plymouth Co. by one day, although there are multiple November records in Massachusetts. Clearly two different birds, as they were found ~1.25 km away from each other, and the habitat is broken by large gaps. In addition, the first bird was left at 09:15, and the second bird was found at 09:55. Told from Philadelphia by the overall washed out facial pattern; i.e. the cap and lores were pale gray, not dark like in Philadelphia. Yellow was restricted to the flanks and undertail coverts. They are likely both HYs due to the outer rectrices coming to fine, tapered points, whereas adults should have more round-tipped outer rectrices. Observation Details: Along the canal just south of Sunset (the Pacific Wren spot from the 22-23 winter). Vireo with no wingbars. Olive above, whitish below with some yellowish green wash on the lower flanks and at the bend of the wing. Gray legs. Indistinct whitish supercilium, grayish crown, pale lores. Dark eye. Did not vocalize. Pale lores and the fact that the upper breast and lower throat lacked yellow and were not the most yellow parts of the underparts rule out Philadelphia Vireo. Watched through 10x binoculars at about 20 yards, about 15 feet up in trees, for several minutes. Photos attached. First local winter record and a good six weeks past prior late fall records. The weather has been very mild so far this fall.

Observation Details: Added my first image of the bird on 15-Aug-2023, which gives, in my opinion, a better sense of the medium gray topsides and non-black crown. Original comments:  Adult WAVI, not sub-adult REVI. Photographed bird has: Very pale yellow flanks and undersides;  "plain-faced;" no wing bars.  Light grayish line through eye with practically white lores. rounded head; grayish topsides; dark eye; uniform, dark grayish crown; long tail and very light yellow vent. REVI should have: Some greenish/yellow topsides.  Black line through eye should be darker, especially in the lores. Crown should be dark grayish with distinctive black lining above the supercilium; facial disc should sharp light and dark areas, not the "soft" look of a WAVI facial disc; short tailed and yellow vent; larger bill; yellower in neck and face; PHVI: Smaller billed; smaller size than WAVI; darker and longer line through eye on PHVI; PHVI has central yellow wash in upper breast.. A first August record for Kerr Co.  Extremely few records this early In August in the surrounding counties. Bird made sweeps into the water feature, barely touching the water for a fraction of a second to get wet, then preened in Ash.

**Very rare! Found yesterday midday on CBC by Roger Horn, and also observed and photographed at dusk yesterday by TBJ and me. Foraging and roving about the roadside hedge very energetically in the morning sun. Only prior December eBird records in the east north of Florida of any Warbling Vireo are singles from NS, OH, MD, NC, GA. Occurrence of “Western” in the east clouded in uncertainty due to difficulty of field ID, but certainly very rare. This individual had retained juvenile wing coverts and a strikingly small bill, the former trait apparently diagnostic for swainsoni at this date, and the latter strongly supportive, and at this extreme perhaps also diagnostic. [see “Voelker, G., and S. Rohwer (1998). Contrasts in scheduling of molt and migration in eastern and western Warbling Vireos. Auk 115 (1):142-155,” as well as “Pyle - Identification Guide to North American Birds. Part I,”] A targeted examination of specimens at the AMNH after this observation was also consistent with the above resources. Poop sample collected some time after this observation, and will potentially undergo DNA analysis at ANSP. Excellent close views this morning, and good photos (best by TBJ on different checklist) and video.

Refound today by Bob Curry as it flitted about in shrubs and low tree branches, mostly at, slightly above or below eye level. It was very active catching prey (flying insect in one photo) on the southeast side, sheltered from the wind. Grey crown and nape, greenish-grey mantle and white below with pale yellow wash on flanks. White supercilium and lores. Pale bill with dark tip. Faint line behind eye. Seen first on 29 November by Julie Bowen, then Ana Santos, and reported on 1 December by Laura Murray. Great winter bird. Record late for the GTA - per Glenn Coady on Ontario Bird Alert Discord.

One or two. Had the chance to watch a WAVI that had apparently just grabbed a large katydid, low in willows along the creek. As this was where I could get a good view of the action, I started taking lots of photos. First saw it appear out in open, with its large meal being grasped by one foot(!) as it perched on a willow branch. Surprised that the katydid wasn't putting up much of a struggle it seemed, at least during the time I was watching them. The WAVI first started working on the insect's head and fairly soon had bitten off the head. It then seemed to take its time and began working on the thorax area. The katydid must have a fairly hard exoskeleton as the bird didn't seem to be making much  progress, that I could see at least, on the thorax area. But then, after maybe a couple minutes of watching this, the vireo moved back a few feet into the cover of the willows where it was hard to observe (or photo) anything further, so left the WAVI to enjoy its feast.

Observation Details: Very drab individual showing nondescript facial markings in comparison to nearby Red-eyed Vireo, shorter bill, not as lanky body shape with more chunkiness to it. Separated from more expected Philadelphia Vireo by lack of stronger yellow on the chest/throat than on the stomach (brightest yellow appears on flanks), pink bill base noted by Matt Hafner as a helpful mark for WAVI vs. PHVI as well through correspondence after the observation. Photographs are cropped but are otherwise not edited so the colors remain exactly how the camera received them in the field.
